SIMPLE: rumor
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rumor
<hw>Ru"mor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>rumeur</ets>,
L. <ets>rumor</ets>; cf. <ets>rumificare</ets>, <ets>rumitare</ets> to
rumor, Skr. <ets>ru</ets> to cry.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>rumour</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A flying or popular report;
the common talk; hence, public fame; notoriety.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>rumor</qex> of him went forth throughout all Judea, and
throughout all the region round about.</q> <rj><qau>Luke vii.
17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great is the <qex>rumor</qex> of this dreadful knight.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A current story passing from one person to another,
without any known authority for its truth; -- in this sense often
personified.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Rumor</qex> next, and Chance,⟦br⟧
And Tumult, and Confusion, all embroiled.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A prolonged, indistinct noise.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rumor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rumor
<hw>Ru"mor</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Rumored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rumoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To report by rumor; to
tell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T was <qex>rumored</qex>⟦br⟧
My father 'scaped from out the citadel.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rumorer</ent>⟦br⟧
